Forecasting in R

In this tutorial, well examine the tools for forecasting in R, or modeling with time data.

Well refer often to the excellent online text Forecasting: Principles and Practice by Rob Hyndman.

Packages needed

For this module, you will need the following packages:

# install.packages("tidyverse","lubridate","forecast","tsibble","tsbox","fpp2","xts","urca")

Forecasting and prediction

Forecasting is predicting the future, given past data.

Forecasts are often sub-categorized as short-, medium-, and long-term, depending on how far out the forecasts reach, and whether they concentrate on topics such as scheduling, resource management, or strategic planning.

In forecasting the data is a time series, with some time component that has a frequency and may have seasonality or cycles. Models used for forecasting include simple methods, linear models and ARIMA.

What is a forecast?

A forecast is a prediction of possible future values. It is often accompanied by a prediction interval giving a range of probable values for the variable. A forecast is the average value of a forecast distribution, which is the probability distribution of the future of our random variable, given our past data.

Time series

A time series object in R is a particular class that represents a vector of measurements, along with information about when those measurements were recorded.

The core time series object in R is the ts object, and R comes bundled with several built in time series data sets.

When you plot a time series, R defaults to a line plot.

Constructing a time series

You can construct a time series by providing your observations as well as a start time and frequency.

When you construct a frequency in a ts, the following integer values give you the daily, weekly or yearly frequency.

Frequency Value
Annual 1
Quarterly 4
Monthly 12
Weekly 52 
x <- rnorm(10) #some random numbers from a standard normal distribution
y <- ts(x,start=2000) #made into a time series starting at year 2000
# default frequency is yearly (1)
y
## Time Series:
## Start = 2000 
## End = 2009 
## Frequency = 1

class(y)
## [1] "ts"
plot(y)

ymon <- ts(x,start = 2018, frequency = 12)

Multiple time formats

For more functionality, there are other time series objects. In fact, there are many competing formats, such as xts, zoo, and others.

The built-in ts object works best for regular time series data on a yearly, quarterly or monthly frequency. xts extends this functionality to include irregular frequency and the possibility of using time formats.

One notable modern variant of the time series is the tsibble. A tsibble is a time series tibble. It looks like a data frame, with a datetime column marked as an index.

Here, well convert our time series to a xts and a tsibble using as.xts() and as_tsibble().

In the conversion below, the data is reshaped into a long format.

We can also use the tsbox package to convert between time series formats.

library(xts)
library(tsibble)
library(tsbox)

All about tsibbles

Well take a look at the tsibble format in more depth, and then return to using ts and xts objects for forecasting.

Why tsibble?

In the R ecosystem, there are several overlapping time series formats: ts, xts, and zoo being the most notable. They all add functionality to the core ts class, however tsibble attempts to bring time series treatment inline with the tidyverse principles, including chaining and piping operations. Its built on top of a tibble and a time series, hence the name.

Creating a tsibble

We can bring data in and cast it to a tsibble with as_tsibble.

A tsibble requires a datetime index and a key which defines the subjects or individuals tracked over time.

The combination of key and index uniquely identify each observation.

It can automatically choose the time index, or the index can be explicitly specified.

Types of intervals

From the tsibble vignette, these are the types of intervals that can be specified

An interval is automatically obtained based on the corresponding time representation:

integer/numeric/ordered: either unit or year (Y)  
yearquarter/yearqtr: quarter (Q)
yearmonth/yearmon: month (M)
yearweek: week (W)
Date: day (D)
difftime: quarter (Q), month (M), week (W), day (D), hour (h), minute (m), second (s)
POSIXct/hms: hour (h), minute (m), second (s), millisecond (us), microsecond (ms)
nanotime: nanosecond (ns)

Window functions

Tsibbles provide three variants of moving window operations, verbs that operate on temporal data objects.

  • slide() provides a sliding window with overlapping observations
  • tile() provides a tiling window without overlaps
  • stretch() fixes an initial window and can expand to more observations

These functions play well with purrr::map()

Calculating moving averages

The moving average is a commonly used approach to smooth the noisiness of a time series. Its calculated by sliding a window along the index and averaging values within that window.

Visualizing time series

The autoplot method of ggplot can visualize a time series using ggplot2 methods. Because it is built on top of ggplot2, we can use our ggplot modifiers, like changing axis labels, titles, and themes.

For many of the functions in forecast, we need to use ts objects. Tsibble objects sometimes work, but well concentrate on ts for now.

Note: the team behind forecast is working on a tidy forecasting package called fable, but at the time of writing it seems not quite ready, so well save that for a future lesson.

library(forecast)
library(ggplot2)
autoplot(ymon)+theme_minimal()

Trends, seasons, cycles

Time series can be composed of trends, seasonality or cycles, and we can separate these components.

  • Trend: long-term increase or decrease, not necessarily linear.
  • Seasonality: an effect by time of year or day of week, of a fixed and known frequency.
  • Cycles: rises and falls that are not of a fixed frequency.
    • in general, cycle length is greater that seasonal length
    • magnitudes of cycles tend to be larger than seasonal patterns
# showing a cyclic pattern
autoplot(lynx) + theme_minimal()

# does the release of co2 from Mauna Loa have a  pattern? 
autoplot(co2) + theme_minimal()

Seasonal and subseries plot

The seasonal plot can provide a clear window onto seasonality. It automatically groups by the frequency term.

The subseries plot is a small multiple across the sub-division frequency.

# these plots are from the forecast library
ggseasonplot(co2)+theme(legend.position = "none")

# no seasonality trend
ggsubseriesplot(co2)

#
#ggseasonplot(lynx) # data are not seasonal, gives error

Faceted time plots

In the case of several variables in a time series, it may be helpful to plot them all on a common axis.

We can accomplish that with a tsibble.

plot(EuStockMarkets) # this works because the data have already been arranged into a ts with multiple variables.

esm_tsb <- as_tsibble(EuStockMarkets)
#autoplot(esm_tsb) + theme_minimal() # this also correctly plots the time series on a single axis.
# this is an equivalent to using a grouping variable on a long data set
ggplot(esm_tsb,aes(x=index,y=value,color=key))+geom_line()+theme_minimal()

Autocorrelation plots

Autocorrelation plots display the relationship between lagged values of a time series. The ACF or autocorrelation function calculates these relationships, and we can display them as a plot along a lag axis.

The dashed blue lines indicate autocorrelations that are significantly different from 0.

With seasonal data, you might observe a slight scalloped shape that is due to the seasonal component.

"When data have a trend, the autocorrelations for small lags tend to be large and positive because observations nearby in time are also nearby in size. So the ACF of trended time series tend to have positive values that slowly decrease as the lags increase.

When data are seasonal, the autocorrelations will be larger for the seasonal lags (at multiples of the seasonal frequency) than for other lags." forecasting

# seasonal autocorrelation - notice a slight scalloped shape in the plot
ggAcf(co2)

# no autocorrelation
ggAcf(ymon)

# cyclic but not seasonal autocorrelation in the lynx data.
ggAcf(lynx)

Make an autoplot and an acf plot of your mpg_ts.

Simple and naive forecasts

Many simple forecasting methods are surprisingly effective. We summarize them here:

  • average: forecasts of future values are the mean of historic values
  • naive: forecasts are set at the last value observed
  • naive-seasonal: forecast are set at the last seasonal value observed
  • drift: draw a line from the first to last observations, and extrapolate it

We can create these forecasts with a time series and forecasting functions provided in the forecast package. Here we visualize them, in the next section well demonstrate how to use them.

For each, we specify a forward horizon (h=)

library(forecast)

Residuals

We can extract residuals from forecasts using the residuals function. Residuals are the errors, or the difference between the observations and fitted values of the forecast. These are only available for methods that are not true forecasts into the unobserved future.

From Forecasting: "Residuals are useful in checking whether a model has adequately captured the information in the data. A good forecasting method will yield residuals with the following properties:

  1. The residuals are uncorrelated. If there are correlations between residuals, then there is information left in the residuals which should be used in computing forecasts.
  2. The residuals have zero mean. If the residuals have a mean other than zero, then the forecasts are biased.

residuals(forecast) gives the residuals or errors from a forecast

snaive_co2 <- snaive(co2, h=20)
tail(co2)
##         Jul    Aug    Sep    Oct    Nov    Dec
## 1997 364.52 362.57 360.24 360.83 362.49 364.34
resd <- residuals(snaive_co2) 
tail(resd)
##       Jul  Aug  Sep  Oct  Nov  Dec
## 1997 0.82 1.03 0.73 1.18 1.69 1.96
autoplot(resd)+theme_minimal()

ggAcf(resd) # there is still correlaiton in the residuals 

gghistogram(resd) # these don't have a zero mean

Stationarity and differencing

A stationary time series has properties that do not depend on the time component. Thus time series with trend or seasonal components are not stationery.

High ACF often indicates a non-stationary series.

Differencing or computing differences between consecutive observations, can make a time series stationary, and can stabilize the mean of the series.

Sometimes second-order differencing (taking the difference of the differenced values) might also be called for. Differencing is accomplished with the diff() function.

We can test the need for differencing with the KPSS test (ur.kpss()) from the urca package. We can also check the number of differences needed with the ndiffs() function.

A related function is to check the number of seasonal differences needed, or nsdiffs().

Linear Models

We can fit a linear regression model using the forecast variable as our y or dependent variable, and predictor variables.

For time series, we can use the tslm function instead of the lm function. This will create a model object with a bit more functionality with respect to time series. However, we could use the lm function if we choose. One feature of tslm is that it creates trend and season components on-the-fly from the time series.

In evaluating the linear model, we will examine the residuals, to check if they are autocorrelated (with an acf plot) and if they are approximately normal and centered around 0 (with a histogram.) The forecast package bundles these nicely into a checkresiduals function.

Here, we model the dataset uschange.

tslm(formula,data) fit a time series linear model
checkresiduals(fit) convenience function for tsmodel diagnostics

Linear ts components

As mentioned, the tslm() function makes it simple to add a number of time-series relevant components to a linear model.

  • + trend adds a trend component to the model
  • + season will add seasonal dummy variables to a model. If you have a weekly frequency, for example, it will add indication variables for the days of the week.

Other possible components include easter() for calculating the effect of the easter holiday, and fourier() transforms. See the book for more details.

Regression forecasts

To make forecasts from regression, we distinguish between the kinds of forecasts made by what is known at the time of the forecast.

Ex-ante forecasts are made with the data available in advance. To make ex-ante forecasts, we need to create forecasts of the predictors as well. If use seasonal components or calendar time as predictors, we know what these will be in the future.

Ex-post forecasts are made using later information from the predictors. These are not genuine forecasts, but can use be used to study the behaviour of the models.

We can use the forecast method to retrieve forecasts. If we need to supply new data, we can construct that as a data frame.

h <- 4
# scenario of constant growth of 1% in Income and 0.5% in Savings
newdata <- 
  data.frame(Income = rep(1,h),
                      Production = rep(0,h),
                      Savings = rep(0.5,h),
                      Unemployment = rep(0,h))
fcast <- 
  forecast(fit,newdata=newdata)
autoplot(uschange[,1])+autolayer(fcast,PI=T,series="growth")+theme_minimal()

Holt-Winters forecast

We can make a Holt-Winters forecast, which is a forecast based on exponential smoothing and components for season and trend. Holt-Winters has two variants, an additive or a multiplicative method. The multiplicative method is preferred when seasonal variations are changing proportional to the level of the series, whereas we use the additive method when the seasonal component is expressed in absolute terms in the scale of the observed series.

Here are example methods of Holt-Winters forecasts with the ausbeer data.

hw(ts,seasonal="additive",h=8)

ETS Model

In fact, Holt-Winters forecasts are related to a family of forecast methods called ETS for Error, Trend, Seasonal or state space models. Each model can have additive or multiplicative errors.

To choose from all the combinations of ETS models, we can use either AIC (Akaikes Information Criterion), AICc (corrected), or BIC.

To create an ets model, we can use the ets() function. Unlike earlier forecast methods, however, this function doesnt generate point estimates, but estimates model parameters and returns information on the fitted model, much like the lm function. If we dont use any of the optional arguments, ets attempts to automatically fit an appropriate model.

For mathematical details of ETS models, read here.

ETS forecast

To retrieve the forecast from an ETS model, we use the forecast() method on our fit, and specify the horizon.

ARIMA Model

In an autoregressive model, we make forecasts using linear combinations of past values of the variable. Moving average models forecast uses past forecast errors in a regression-like model. Combining autoregressive and moving average models yields the ARIMA model.

To fit an ARIMA model, we can use the auto.arima function from the forecast package. There are built in arima functions as well in base R. The auto.arima function will try several different models, and choose a best candidate by comparing AIC. You can read details on the algorithm here.

Here, we fit a model to the uschange data using auto.arima.

fit_arima1 <- 
  auto.arima(uschange[,"Consumption"],
             seasonal = FALSE)
summary(fit_arima1)

Conclusion

There are many more methods to explore in the realm of forecasting. There are additional details about ARIMA models to explore, comparisons with ETS, and dynamic regression models and hierarchical time series. We invite you to continue with the Forecasting book to explore these advanced topics.

As mentioned earlier, the team behind the forecast package is also working on a tidy forecasting package called fable. We look forward to its full release to explore how it will interface with the tidy time series tsibble. Until then, happy forecasting!
